post_title: If I applied 20 gigajoules of energy to a 1kg mass, how fast would it go? The Newtonian answer is 200,000 m/s, which is obviously wrong, since that's faster than the speed of light. How do I make this calculation taking relativity into consideration?

======================================================

(You): If I applied 20 gigajoules of energy to a 1kg mass, how fast would it go? The Newtonian answer is 200,000 m/s, which is obviously wrong, since that's faster than the speed of light. How do I make this calculation taking relativity into consideration?

(Roberto): speed of light is 3x10^8 m/s. So your calculation is valid.

(You): OK, but what if I applied 80GJ -- that would put the result at 400000 km/s

(Roberto): If K is the kinetic energy and m the mass then v=sqrt(2*K/m). So, even with K=80GJ, v is still 4x10^5 meters per sec, not Km per sec

(You): thanks, my bad.

(Roberto): no problem. if you want to know what happens if you enter the relativisti regime you should use the formula K=(gamma-1)*m*c^2, where gamma=(v/c)^2, c being the speed of light.

(You): thanks. Oddly, your colon parentheses was turned into a frowny face by google chat :) I actually did look up the relativistic equations later.

