(Wouter): The speed of light is 300,000 km/s, so you are not there yet by a factor 1000.  But anyway, take a look at the formulas in http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kinetic_energy#Relativistic_kinetic_energy_of_rigid_bodies .  Whatever energy you add (20 GJ) is pure kinetic energy, and those formulas will allow you to determine v/c, the fraction of the light speed (always smaller than 1).  The faster an object goes, the more energy you need to get the same increase in velocity.  That is the difference with Newtonian mechanics.

